What is the probability that a randomly chosen real number from the interval $[0,1]$ has a $3$ in its decimal expansion?

-
It is the same as the probability that a randomly chosen real number from the interval $[0,1]$ has a $3$ in its binary expansion. –  Thomas Andrews Feb 25 at 22:05
The probability is $1$. –  Thomas Andrews Feb 25 at 22:06
@ThomasAndrews If that is true then the probability that a randomly chosen real number from the interval $[0,1]$ has a $2$ in its decimal expansion is also $1$. But that is not true. –  Stefan Feb 25 at 22:07
@Stefan It is true. –  Thomas Andrews Feb 25 at 22:08
@ThomasAndrews I think that is because of the fact that you don't have to choose only one digit. You can choose several digits. But that is not the question. –  Stefan Feb 25 at 22:10

The probability is $1$. For any real number $x$ in $[0,1]$ there is a binary expansion $x=\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{a_n}{2^n}$ such that $x=\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{a_n}{10^n}$.

-
But the probability that a randomly chosen real number from the interval $[0,1]$ has a $2$ in its decimal expansion is not $1$. –  Stefan Feb 25 at 22:05
@Stefan The probability is $1$ for the same reason. –  Thomas Andrews Feb 25 at 22:06
@ThomasAndrews No, it is not. –  Stefan Feb 25 at 22:07
@Stefan I think you are just being pedantic. –  Thomas Andrews Feb 25 at 22:09
@Stefan The probability is $1$ for the same reason. –  Thomas Andrews Feb 25 at 22:10

